vez.en-plu: like once upon a time or two times

present.etymologie: Latin praesentem (nominative praesens) "present, at hand, in sight; immediate; prompt, instant; contemporary," from present participle of præesse "be before (someone or something), be at hand," from prae- "before" (see pre-) + esse "to be" (from PIE root *es- "to be"). Meaning "being there" is from mid-14c. in English. As a grammatical tense, recorded from late 14c.

pensa.en-plu: can be a thought (noun, active sense)

afere.etymologie: c. 1300, "what one has to do, ordinary business," from Anglo-French afere, Old French afaire "business, event; rank, estate" (12c., Modern French affaire), from the infinitive phrase à faire "to do," from Latin ad "to" (see ad-) + facere "to do, make" (from PIE root *dhe- "to set, put").

actual.etymologie: early 14c., "pertaining to acts or an action;" late 14c. in the broader sense of "real, existing" (as opposed to potential, ideal, etc.); from Old French actuel "now existing, up to date" (13c.), from Late Latin actualis "active, pertaining to action," adjectival form of Latin actus "a doing" (from PIE root *ag- "to drive, draw out or forth, move").

moment.etymologie: contraction of *movimentum, from movere "to move" (from PIE root *meue- "to push away").

ea.en-plu: in a general sense of movement
